<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, <b>Spearman's rank correlation coefficient</b> or <b>S=
pearman's <i>=CF=81</i></b> is a number ranging from -1 to 1 that indicates=
 how strongly two sets of ranks are correlated. It could be used in a situa=
tion where one only has ranked data, such as a tally of gold, silver, and b=
ronze medals. If a statistician wanted to know whether people who are high =
ranking in sprinting are also high ranking in long-distance running, they w=
ould use a Spearman rank correlation coefficient.
</p><p>The coefficient is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Charles_Spearman" title=3D"Charles Spearman">Charles Spearman</a><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and of=
ten denoted by the Greek letter <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rh=
o_(letter)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rho (letter)"><span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \rho }">
