d dependence">statistical dependence</a> between the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranking_(statistics)" title=3D"Ranking (statistics)">ran=
kings</a> of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(mathema=
tics)#Applied_statistics" title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">variables</a>). =
It assesses how well the relationship between two variables can be describe=
d using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" titl=
e=3D"Monotonic function">monotonic function</a>.
</p><p>The Spearman correlation between two variables is equal to the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_product-moment_correlation_coef=
ficient" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson product-moment correlation =
coefficient">Pearson correlation</a> between the rank values of those two v=
ariables; while Pearson's correlation assesses linear relationships, Spearm=
an's correlation assesses monotonic relationships (whether linear or not). =
If there are no repeated data values, a perfect Spearman correlation of +1 =
or =E2=88=921 occurs when each of the variables is a perfect monotone funct=
ion of the other.
</p><p>Intuitively, the Spearman correlation between two variables will be =
high when observations have a similar (or identical for a correlation of 1)=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranking_(statistics)" title=3D"Ra=
nking (statistics)">rank</a> (i.e. relative position label of the observati=
ons within the variable: 1st, 2nd, 3rd, etc.) between the two variables, an=
d low when observations have a dissimilar (or fully opposed for a correlati=
on of =E2=88=921) rank between the two variables.
</p><p>Spearman's coefficient is appropriate for both <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Con=
