<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Related_quantities">Related=
 quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3=
" title=3D"Edit section: Related quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_and_dependence" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Correlation and dependence">Correlation and depe=
ndence</a></div>
<p>There are several other numerical measures that quantify the extent of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_dependence" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Statistical dependence">statistical dependence</a> betw=
een pairs of observations. The most common of these is the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_product-moment_correlation_coefficient" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient=
">Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient</a>, which is a similar co=
rrelation method to Spearman's rank, that measures the "linear" relationshi=
ps between the raw numbers rather than between their ranks.
</p><p>An alternative name for the Spearman <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Rank_correlation" title=3D"Rank correlation">rank correlation</a>=
 is the "grade correlation";<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Yule_and_Kendall_9-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_c=
orrelation_coefficient#cite_note-Yule_and_Kendall-9"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in this, th=
e "rank" of an observation is replaced by the "grade". In continuous distri=
butions, the grade of an observation is, by convention, always one half les=
s than the rank, and hence the grade and rank correlations are the same in =
this case. More generally, the "grade" of an observation is proportional to=
 an estimate of the fraction of a population less than a given value, with =
the half-observation adjustment at observed values. Thus this corresponds t=
o one possible treatment of tied ranks. While unusual, the term "grade corr=
elation" is still in use.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficien=
t#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretation">Interpretat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpearman=
%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=
=3D"Edit section: Interpretation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><div class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner=
" style=3D"width:608px;max-width:608px"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"t=
header">Positive and negative Spearman rank correlations</div></div><div cl=
ass=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:302px;max-width:302px"><=
div class=3D"thumbimage"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/File:Spearman_fig5.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img =
alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/S=
pearman_fig5.svg/330px-Spearman_fig5.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"3=
00" height=3D"284" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"360" data-f=
ile-height=3D"341"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption">A positive =
Spearman correlation coefficient corresponds to an increasing monotonic tre=
nd between <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i>.</div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=
=3D"width:302px;max-width:302px"><div class=3D"thumbimage"><span typeof=3D"=
mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Spearman_fig4.svg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Spearman_fig4.svg/330px-Spearman_fig4.svg.=
png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"284" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"360" data-file-height=3D"341"></a></span></div><div =
class=3D"thumbcaption">A negative Spearman correlation coefficient correspo=
nds to a decreasing monotonic trend between <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i>.</div></d=
iv></div></div></div>
<p>The sign of the Spearman correlation indicates the direction of associat=
ion between <i>X</i> (the independent variable) and <i>Y</i> (the dependent=
 variable).  If  <i>Y</i> tends to increase when <i>X</i> increases, the Sp=
earman correlation coefficient is positive.  If <i>Y</i> tends to decrease =
when <i>X</i> increases, the Spearman correlation coefficient is negative. =
 A Spearman correlation of zero indicates that there is no tendency for <i>=
Y</i> to either increase or decrease when <i>X</i> increases.  The Spearman=
 correlation increases in magnitude as <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> become closer =
to being perfectly monotonic functions of each other.  When <i>X</i> and <i=
>Y</i> are perfectly monotonically related, the Spearman correlation coeffi=
cient becomes 1.  A perfectly monotonic increasing relationship implies tha=
t for any two pairs of data values <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i><sub><i>=
i</i></sub>, <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>X</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>, <i>Y</i><sub><i>j</i></sub></span>, that <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> =E2=88=92 <i>X</i><sub><i>j=
</i></sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> =
=E2=88=92 <i>Y</i><sub><i>j</i></sub></span> always have the same sign.  A =
perfectly monotonic decreasing relationship implies that these differences =
always have opposite signs.
</p><p>The Spearman correlation coefficient is often described as being "no=
nparametric".  This can have two meanings.  First, a perfect Spearman corre=
lation results when <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> are related by any <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" title=3D"Monotonic function"=
>monotonic function</a>. Contrast this with the Pearson correlation, which =
only gives a perfect value when <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> are related by a <i>l=
inear</i> function. The other sense in which the Spearman correlation is no=
nparametric is that its exact sampling distribution can be obtained without=
 requiring knowledge (i.e., knowing the parameters) of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_probability_distribution" title=3D"Joint pro=
bability distribution">joint probability distribution</a> of <i>X</i> and <=
i>Y</i>.
</p>
