=3D{\sqrt {\frac {n-3}{1.06}}}F(r)}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_score" title=3D"S=
tandard score"><i>z</i>-score</a> for <i>r</i>, which approximately follows=
 a standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" t=
itle=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> under the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">nul=
l hypothesis</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_in=
dependence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical independence">statis=
tical independence</a> (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i> =3D 0</span>)=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-12"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-13"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>One can also test for significance using
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e t=3Dr{\sqrt {\frac {n-2}{1-r^{2}}}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>t</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <msup>
                  <mi>r</mi>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msup>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle t=3Dr{\sqrt {=
\frac {n-2}{1-r^{2}}}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5457d4ac0d9126250ae19dc9c1f5448cd8b9ec7c" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.171ex; width:14.899ex; height:7.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle t=
=3Dr{\sqrt {\frac {n-2}{1-r^{2}}}},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>which is distributed approximately as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution" title=3D"Student's t-distribution">Stude=
nt's <i>t</i>-distribution</a> with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=88=
=92 2</span> degrees of freedom under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 A justification for this result relies on a permutation argument.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A generalization of the Spearman coefficient is useful in the situat=
ion where there are three or more conditions, a number of subjects are all =
observed in each of them, and it is predicted that the observations will ha=
ve a particular order.  For example, a number of subjects might each be giv=
en three trials at the same task, and it is predicted that performance will=
 improve from trial to trial.  A test of the significance of the trend betw=
een conditions in this situation was developed by E. B. Page<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spear=
man%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and is usual=
ly referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Page%27s_trend_t=
est" title=3D"Page's trend test">Page's trend test</a> for ordered alternat=
ives.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Correspondence_analysis_bas=
ed_on_Spearman's_=CF=81"><span id=3D"Correspondence_analysis_based_on_Spear=
man.27s_.CF.81"></span>Correspondence analysis based on Spearman's <i>=CF=
=81</i></h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpea=
rman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Correspondence analysis based on Spearman's =CF=81"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>Classic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correspondence_analysis=
" title=3D"Correspondence analysis">correspondence analysis</a> is a statis=
tical method that gives a score to every value of two nominal variables. In=
 this way the Pearson <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_prod=
uct-moment_correlation_coefficient" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson =
product-moment correlation coefficient">correlation coefficient</a> between=
 them is maximized.
</p><p>There exists an equivalent of this method, called <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGrade_correspondence_analysis&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Grade correspondence ana=
lysis (page does not exist)">grade correspondence analysis</a>, which maxim=
izes Spearman's <i>=CF=81</i> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K=
endall%27s_%CF%84" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kendall's =CF=84">Kendall=
's =CF=84</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spearman%27s_rank_correlation_coefficient#cite_note=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Approximating_Spearman's_=
=CF=81_from_a_stream"><span id=3D"Approximating_Spearman.27s_.CF.81_from_a_=
stream"></span>Approximating Spearman's <i>=CF=81</i> from a stream</h2><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSpearman%27s_rank_c=
orrelation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Approximating Spearman's =CF=81 from a stream"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are two existing approaches to approximating the Spearman's rank c=
